content.description: The forked chimney at the south (right) end of Elephant Rocks.  Head up the initial chimney, then surmount the small bulge between the upper chimneys to the final hand crack.Pronounced "hot tea", with the accent on the first syllable - Nepali for "elephant".
content.protection: Standard rack with a couple of hand-sized pieces.
content.location: At the south end of Elephant Rocks, the slot facing the Lake.  The upper hand crack is visible from the ground.  Well right of Two Cracks, left of Romancing the Bone.

content.description: Great route that follows two finger cracks and some face holds up the face.  Don't wander too far right or you'll be off route, as you would be on most routes at Devil's Lake...
content.protection: Standard rack, refresh me if this is wrong.  It's been a while since I've climbed here.
content.location: Just to the right of Tomb of the Unknown Homo on the South face of the South buttress of Elephant Rocks.

content.description: Right of Dumbo(5.9), climb up pillar to ledge, and continue up inside corner to top.As a leadable variation, climb the left crack of Tomb of the Unkown, then continue into the upper corner.  You'll miss the "trunk", but still fun.
content.protection:
For The Trunk proper, no gear on the lower arete.  Tiny, shallow gear in the upper corner.  Big gear for the anchor at the top.

 For the variations, a standard rack plus tiny gear.
content.location: North face of South Buttress of Elephant Rocks

content.description: Interesting outside corner with a crack.
content.protection: Never looked at the gear, someone fill me in if you can remember.
content.location: On the Southwest outside corner of the North buttress of Elephant Rocks.

content.description: Climb the crack and chimney system to the top.   (aka "Tomb of the Unknown Homo")
content.location: On the South face of the South buttress of Elephant rocks.  Found just right of the corner.

content.description: Climb the bone-like rock in the center of the southeast face of Elephant Rocks. The bone is formed by 2 off-width cracks that split the face into thirds. Climb using only the bone, and not the rocks on either side of the off-width cracks.
content.location: On the southeast face of the Elephant Rocks area. There is a clear view of it from the East Bluff Trail.

content.description: Fingertip layback to the level of the "Tomb."  Then continue up the outside corner to the right with another layback move or two.
content.protection: Small (finger-sized) gear.  A couple of fist-sized pieces for the belay.
content.location: To the right of "Tomb" is a left-facing fingertip dihedral.

content.description: Obvious easy-looking inside corner to the left of Transcendental Disfiguration.
Don't have time to romance the bone? Climb the off-width crack on the left of the bone. There's a nice spot for an arm-bar if you choose to use it.
content.location: On the southeast face of the Elephant Rocks area. There is a clear view of it from the East Bluff Trail.

content.description: Climb the face left of the deep crack and pillar (left of Dumbo). Climb on thin edges working through a mantle onto a ledge halfway up. Lieback or crimp the face above the ledge. Avoid holds used to climb the crack.
content.protection: Don't recall there being much, or any, gear on this route, unless you wanted to use side-gear in the deep crack just right of the route.
content.location: About 6 feet left of the deep crack that's just left of Dumbo. Described as route #4 in Swartling's 3rd Ed.

content.description: A little warm up climb before some serious romance. Climb the off-width crack to the right of the bone.
content.location: On the southeast face of the Elephant Rocks area. There is a clear view of it from the East Bluff Trail.

content.description: Climb the wide cracks left of Dumbo.
content.protection: Wide stuff up to a #6 C4.
content.location: North face of South buttress of Elephant Rocks

content.description: Climb lower inside corner to pillar above, avoiding (in typical DL fashion) anything that would make the route easier than 5.9, particularly the ledge on The Trunk(5.7) its neighbor to the right.
content.location: North face of South buttress of Elephant Rocks

content.description:
Starts in the small alcove on the South face of the North buttress of Elephant Rocks.  Then follows the thin crack to the top. 

  Variation (5.8):  Also starts in the alcove, but follows the crack that diagonals up and right.
content.protection: Standard DL rack including some micro-nuts.
content.location: On the "cheek" of the elephant's head visible on the South face of the North buttress.

content.description: Cracks and face to the right of Two Cracks (5.10a).

Possibly the best roped climbing the North End has to offer is located at Elephant Rocks. 

  Is it named for the large boulder at the top of the cliff or the apparent elephant's head upon whose cheek Clearasil Spattered Fantasies (10b) lies?  I've never been sure, maybe both. 

  Elephant Rocks contains two buttresses and the amphitheater between them.  Routes will be described accordingly.
